b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe48271.htm)  [Next](sbe48273.htm)\n\n* * *\n\np. 549\n\n26\\. Or on account of its quality as light.\n\nThe 'or' is meant to set aside the view previously stated. The Self extends\nthrough the whole body by means of its quality, viz. knowledge or\nconsciousness. 'As light.' As the light of things abiding in one place--such\nas gems, the sun, and so on--is seen to extend to many places, so the\nconsciousness of the Self dwelling in the heart pervades the entire body. That\nthe knowledge of the knowing subject may extend beyond its substrate, as the\nlight of a luminous body does, we have already explained under the first\nSutra.--But it has been said that the Self is _mere_ knowledge; how then can\nknowledge be said to be a quality--which is something different from the\nessential nature of a thing?--This the next Sutra explains.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: 27. There is distinction as in the case of smell...](sbe48273.htm)\n\n"